Articles: {"abstract": "Samsung Electronics will report its fourth-quarter earnings estimates, the insider trading trial of Mathew Martoma will begin and the European Central Bank will review its monetary policy.", "web_url": "https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/06/business/economy/economic-reports-for-the-week-of-jan-6.html", "snippet": "Samsung Electronics will report its fourth-quarter earnings estimates, the insider trading trial of Mathew Martoma will begin and the European Central Bank will review its monetary policy.", "lead_paragraph": "SAMSUNG EARNINGS 2014 will be a tough year for Samsung Electronics, the largest cellphone and television maker in the world. Its stock recently took a beating amid concerns of slowing profit growth from smartphone sales, and the company is under pressure to continue releasing innovative new products to compete with Apple and a crop of handset makers in China. On Tuesday, when the South Korean giant is expected to report earnings estimates for the fourth quarter, investors will keep a close eye on the company\u2019s sales of cellphones, televisions and other items during the holiday shopping season, the most lucrative time of year for electronics manufacturers. The case may be the last criminal case to emerge from a decade-long investigation of Steven A. Cohen and his SAC Capital Advisors hedge fund, Alexandra Stevenson and Matthew Goldstein write in DealBook. {"abstract": "Joe Belfiore, the corporate vice president of Microsoft Windows Phone, discusses goals for 2014 and the potential upside of the company\u2019s Nokia deal.", "web_url": "https://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/02/23/q-a-with-joe-belfiore-on-the-future-of-windows-phone/", "snippet": "Joe Belfiore, the corporate vice president of Microsoft Windows Phone, discusses goals for 2014 and the potential upside of the company\u2019s Nokia deal.", "lead_paragraph": "Joe Belfiore is the corporate vice president of Microsoft Windows Phone, and he oversees the software that powers handsets using the company\u2019s operating system. Microsoft is expected to close its $7.2 billion deal to buy the handset and services division of Nokia by the end of March. The acquisition will give Microsoft control of both mobile software and hardware, as it looks to expand its 4 percent market share in global smartphone sales. Mr. Belfiore will play a crucial role in Microsoft\u2019s efforts to take on Apple and the cellphone makers that use Google\u2019s Android operating system. {"abstract": "The American Advertising Federation and the Institute for Public Relations announced the winners of several awards.", "web_url": "https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/07/business/media/accounts-and-people-of-note-in-the-advertising-industry.html", "snippet": "The American Advertising Federation and the Institute for Public Relations announced the winners of several awards.", "lead_paragraph": "American Advertising Federation, Washington, named seven executives as the 2014 inductees into the Advertising Hall of Achievement, for ad professionals who are age 40 or under. {"abstract": "Citigroup says it has to cut its third-quarter profit by $600 million because of legal expenses. | Apple chief\u2019s coming out. | Judge approves bankruptcy plan for Stockton, Calif.", "web_url": "https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/31/morning-agenda-citigroups-about-face/", "snippet": "Citigroup says it has to cut its third-quarter profit by $600 million because of legal expenses. | Apple chief\u2019s coming out. | Judge approves bankruptcy plan for Stockton, Calif.", "lead_paragraph": "CITIGROUP CUTS THIRD-QUARTER PROFIT | Citigroup can\u2019t seem to catch a break. On Thursday, the bank startled investors with an announcement that it had to lower its third-quarter profit by $600 million because of \u201crapidly evolving regulatory inquiries and investigations,\u201d DealBook\u2019s Michael Corkery, Peter Eavis and Ben Protess write. Citigroup reported its results for the quarter two weeks ago, just before the legal development arose. Although the bank did not specify the development, people briefed on the matter attributed the nearly 18 percent drop in earnings to an investigation into whether Citigroup manipulated the price of foreign currencies. {"abstract": "Defying predictions of their demise, personal computers are making a comeback, enticing a niche audience of professional users with power and beauty, and an Apple machine stands out.", "web_url": "https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/25/technology/personaltech/retina-5k-imac-powerful-proof-of-the-pc-renaissance.html", "snippet": "Defying predictions of their demise, personal computers are making a comeback, enticing a niche audience of professional users with power and beauty, and an Apple machine stands out.", "lead_paragraph": "About a year before he died, Steve Jobs  was asked at a conference to predict the future of the market for personal computers. {"abstract": "The Dow dates from a computer-free era when working out the average of 30 stock prices counted as added value. {"abstract": "Starting Monday a group of lawyers and advocates connected to Adnan Syed, the subject of the podcast \u201cSerial,\u201d will debut another podcast, \u201cUndisclosed: The State v. Adnan Syed.\u201d", "web_url": "https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/08/business/media/another-serial-chapter-from-group-of-lawyers.html", "snippet": "Starting Monday a group of lawyers and advocates connected to Adnan Syed, the subject of the podcast \u201cSerial,\u201d will debut another podcast, \u201cUndisclosed: The State v. Adnan Syed.\u201d", "lead_paragraph": "The story behind the hit podcast \u201cSerial\u201d is not over. The podcast focused on the 1999 death of Hae Min Lee, a Maryland teenager, and the subsequent conviction of her former boyfriend, Adnan Syed, who is serving a life sentence for murder. It became the fastest podcast to reach five million downloads, according to Apple. Starting Monday a group of lawyers and advocates connected to Mr. Syed will debut another podcast, \u201cUndisclosed: The State v. Adnan Syed,\u201d which will \u201cexamine and explore the case in greater detail, from an investigatory perspective instead of a narrative one,\u201d according to a statement. \u201cUndisclosed\u201d is being presented by Rabia Chaudry, a lawyer who has been a longtime advocate of Mr. Syed \u2014 as \u201cSerial\u201d fans know, she was the one who suggested that Sarah Koenig, the host of \u201cSerial\u201d and a longtime producer for \u201cThis American Life,\u201d look into the case \u2014 along with two other lawyers, Susan Simpson and Colin Miller. None of them represent Mr. Syed but each has been investigating the case, Ms. Chaudry said in an interview Tuesday. New episodes of \u201cUndisclosed\u201d are to be released every two weeks. The podcast is sponsored by the Adnan Syed Legal Trust, which, according to a page on the crowdfunding site LaunchGood, is dedicated to Mr. Syed\u2019s defense and has raised $93,000. In November the producers of \u201cSerial\u201d said that a second season was coming. In February a Maryland court agreed to hear an appeal from Mr. Syed, who has said that he is not guilty of Ms. Lee\u2019s murder and that he received ineffective legal counsel at trial.", {"abstract": "Greece is expected to pay 4.25 billion euros due on bonds; later this week, earnings reports will be announced by Apple, Morgan Stanley, Credit Suisse and General Motors.", "web_url": "https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/20/business/greeces-debt-payments-apple-earnings-and-credit-suisse-results.html", "snippet": "Greece is expected to pay 4.25 billion euros due on bonds; later this week, earnings reports will be announced by Apple, Morgan Stanley, Credit Suisse and General Motors.", "lead_paragraph": "After receiving a short-term loan from the European Union last week, Greece is expected to pay 4.25 billion euros ($4.6 billion) due on bonds held by the European Central Bank, as well as \u20ac2 billion in overdue payments to the International Monetary Fund. Failure to pay the E.C.B. would have forced the bank to cut off emergency funding for Greek banks, causing them and the Greek economy to collapse. The debt payments represent a step back from the precipice of a eurozone exit for Greece, but the government led by Prime Minister Alexis Tsipras must cope this week with the political turmoil caused by his decision to accept unpleasant conditions set by eurozone creditors in return for financial aid. In a move toward normalcy, Greek banks reopened on Monday. \u2014Jack Ewing", "print_section": "B", "print_page": "2", "source": "The New York Times", "multimedia": [{"rank": 0, "subtype": "xlarge", {"abstract": "Apple\u2019s new \u201cfinancing\u201d plan \u2014 a lease in all but name \u2014 makes available for phones a payment structure that is more familiar in the auto market.", "web_url": "https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/19/your-money/when-is-a-lease-not-a-lease-when-its-an-iphone.html", "snippet": "Apple\u2019s new \u201cfinancing\u201d plan \u2014 a lease in all but name \u2014 makes available for phones a payment structure that is more familiar in the auto market.", "lead_paragraph": "APPLE is offering a new way for consumers to purchase iPhones, and while the company is calling the new system a \u201cfinancing\u201d plan, it is essentially a lease.
